Builds the deterministic bubblewrap (`bwrap`) argv used to launch the sandboxed cage process; this is the single place that translates a `BwrapConfig` into the actual sandbox isolation guarantees.

The one entry point is `build_bwrap_args(c: &BwrapConfig) -> Vec<OsString>`, which returns argv with `"bwrap"` as element 0 (caller does `Command::new(&argv[0]).args(&argv[1..])`) and the cage's real command appended after a literal `"--"` separator. It composes five ordered private helpers — `add_base_isolation`, `add_workspace`, `add_toolchain`, `add_tools_and_rules`, `add_envs` — each pushing flag/value pairs onto the same `Vec<OsString>`; order matters for bwrap semantics (e.g. `--clearenv` must precede `--setenv` calls, which it does since `add_envs` runs last).

Key invariants: `--unshare-net` is always included — the cage is unconditionally offline, with the API proxy socket under `CAGE_RUN_DIR` as the only egress path. `--clearenv` wipes host env, so *only* variables set via `add_envs` are visible to the sandboxed process. The target project is bound read-write at its own real host path (no alias path — this is a deliberate departure from earlier design, referenced as ADR-046), then secret paths within it are individually re-masked read-only with an empty mask file (`c.mask_file`) so secrets are hidden but still present as empty (readers like git shouldn't break on missing files). Toolchain dirs and tool binaries are bound read-only at their *original host paths* (not remapped), so tool configuration (cargo/rustup) resolves normally.

Depends on sibling `super::config` for `BwrapConfig` and the constants `CAGE_BIN`, `CAGE_RULES_PATH`, `CAGE_RUN_DIR` — changing those constants' values changes this file's output paths implicitly. No parsing or validation happens here; this module trusts `BwrapConfig` is already well-formed.